About 6 months ago, I wrote a piece about ETH after my dad asked me to convince him that crypto was an investable asset-class. At the time, it felt important for me to reiterate a thesis after all the gloom that weighted on markets post-FTX. 
https://mirror.xyz/damsondao.eth/hPRhYRQGiCwxUccazSIEwZp1HIW8dxDunjkcHxog87k

I also wanted to establish that to me ETH retained the best risk/reward potential in this industry. After flawlessly going through the Merge, it seemed like Ethereum was finally entering a maturing stage after a hyper-speculative cycle and had begun detaching itself from the rest of crypto assets.

Looking back after 2 quarters, I’m really glad that I had the confidence to double down and foresee that, although regulatory crackdowns were coming, institutional interest in crypto and more organic use cases like  would speed up. 
https://twitter.com/TheBlock__/status/1675574023982313472

While I did not anticipate such a resurgence for Bitcoin, pushed further by the SVB and US regional bank debacle, I feel like the current ETH/BTC level coming back to a yearly low once again give ETH superior expected returns and I look forward to the second half of 2023!

There was a lot of rioting and violence in small concentrated zones after the police killing of a boy last week. A lot of people online are trying to make it about race/immigration (as usual i guess) and there is a lot of misinformation (old videos, completely fake headlines like military coming in etc.)

What it's really about is young people from the 'cités' feel abandoned by the society/system and have been suffering from a long history of police abuse, this was a tipping point. 
While there has been a lot of destruction (mostly in their own neighborhoods which makes it fruitless) it's really not a bad as it seems.
